'''Stephen I''', also''' Saint Stephen,''' ({{lang-hu|I. Szent Istv<U+00E1>n}}; {{lang-la|Sanctus Stephanus}};{{sfn|Zsoldos|2001|p=36}} {{lang-sk|<U+0160>tefan I. or <U+0160>tefan Ve<U+013E>k<U+00FD>}}) was the last [[Grand Prince of the Hungarians]] between 997 and 1000 or 1001, and the first [[King of Hungary]] from 1000 or 1001 until his death in 1038. He was born as '''Vajk''' in [[Esztergom]]. The year of his birth is uncertain, but many details of his life suggest that he was born in or after 975. He was the only son of Grand Prince [[G<U+00E9>za, Grand Prince of the Hungarians|G<U+00E9>za]] and his wife, [[Sarolt]], who was descended from the prominent family of the ''[[Gyula (title)|gyulas]]''. Although both of his parents were baptized, Stephen was the first  member of [[<U+00C1>rp<U+00E1>ds|his family]] to become a devout Christian. He married [[Gisela of Hungary|Gisela of Bavaria]], a scion of the imperial [[Ottonian dynasty]].

After succeeding his father in 997, Stephen had to fight for the throne against his relative, [[Kopp<U+00E1>ny]], who was supported by masses of pagan warriors. He defeated Kopp<U+00E1>ny mainly with the assistance of [[Vecelin]], [[Hont-P<U+00E1>zm<U+00E1>ny#Notable members of the clan|Hont and P<U+00E1>zm<U+00E1>ny]] and other knights of foreign origin, but also with help from native lords. He was crowned on 25 December 1000 or 1 January 1001 with a crown sent by [[Pope Sylvester II]]. In a series of wars against semi-independent tribes and chieftains{{mdash}}including the [[Black Hungarians]] and his uncle, [[Gyula III|Gyula the Younger]]{{mdash}}he unified the [[Carpathian Basin]]. He protected the independence of his kingdom by forcing the invading troops of [[Conrad II, Holy Roman Emperor]] to withdraw from Hungary in 1030.

Stephen established at least one archbishopric, six bishoprics and three Benedictine monasteries; thus the Church in Hungary developed independently of the archbishops of the [[Holy Roman Empire]]. He ensured the spread of Christianity among his subjects with severe punishments. His system of local administration was based on [[Counties of the Kingdom of Hungary|counties]] organized around fortresses and administered by [[Isp<U+00E1>n|royal officials]]. Hungary, which enjoyed a lasting period of peace during his reign, became a preferred route for [[pilgrims]] and merchants traveling between [[Western Europe]] and the [[Holy Land]] or [[Constantinople]].

He survived all of his children, which caused bitter conflicts among his relatives, lasting for decades. He died on 15 August 1038 and was buried in his new basilica, built in [[Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r]] and dedicated to the [[Holy Virgin]]. [[Pope Gregory VII]] [[canonized]] him together with his son, [[Saint Emeric of Hungary|Emeric]], and Bishop [[Gerardo Sagredo|Gerard of Csan<U+00E1>d]] ([[Cenad]], [[Romania]]), in 1083. Stephen is a popular saint in [[Hungary]] and the neighboring territories. In Hungary, his [[feast day]] (celebrated on 20 August) is also a [[Public holidays in Hungary|public holiday]] commemorating the foundation of the state.

==Early years (c. 975<U+2013>997)==
[[File:Chronicon Pictum P037 Szent Istv<U+00E1>n sz<U+00FC>let<U+00E9>se.JPG|thumb|right|190px|alt=Stephen's birth|Stephen's birth depicted in the ''[[Illuminated Chronicle]]'']]
The date of his birth is uncertain, because it was not recorded in contemporaneous documents.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=64}} Hungarian and Polish chronicles written centuries later give three different years: 967, 969 and 975.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=15}} The unanimous testimony of his legends and other Hungarian sources, which state that Stephen was "still an adolescent"<ref>''Hartvic, Life of King Stephen of Hungary'' (ch. 5), p. 381.</ref> in 997, substantiate the reliability of the later year (975).{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=64}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=15}} Stephen's ''Lesser Legend'' adds that he was born in Esztergom.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=64}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=15}}<ref name=Britannica>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Stephen I|url=http://britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/565415/Stephen-I|encyclopedia=[[Encyclop<U+00E6>dia Britannica]]|publisher=Encyclop<U+00E6>dia Britannica, Inc.|year=2008|accessdate=2008-07-29}}</ref> His place of birth also implies that he was born after 972, because his father, [[G<U+00E9>za, Grand Prince of the Hungarians]], chose Esztergom as royal residence around that year.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=64}}

Hungarian chronicles unanimously report that Stephen's mother was [[Sarolt]], a daughter of [[Gyula II|Gyula]], the Hungarian [[gyula (title)|chieftain]] with jurisdiction either in [[Transylvania]]{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=44}} or in the wider region of the confluence of the rivers [[Tisza]] and [[Maros]].{{sfn|S<U+0103>l<U+0103>gean|2005|p=147}} Many historians{{mdash}}including P<U+00E1>l Engel and Gyula Krist<U+00F3>{{mdash}}propose that her father was identical with "Gylas", who had around 952 been baptized in [[Constantinople]] and "remained faithful to Christianity",<ref>''John Skylitzes: A Synopsis of Byzantine History, 811<U+2013>1057'' (ch. 11.5.), p. 231.</ref> according to the Byzantine chronicler, [[John Skylitzes]].{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=24}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=28}} However, this identification is not unanimously accepted; for instance, [[Gy<U+00F6>rgy Gy<U+00F6>rffy]] proposes that it was not Sarolt's father, but his younger brother who was baptized in the Byzantine capital.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=44}} In contrast with all Hungarian sources, the ''[[Polish-Hungarian Chronicle]]'' and later [[Poles|Polish]] sources state that Stephen's mother was Adelhaid, an otherwise unknown sister of Duke [[Mieszko I of Poland]], but the reliability of this report is dubious.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=46}}
[[File:Benczur-vajk.jpg|thumb|left|190px|alt=Painting by Gyula Bencz<U+00FA>r|''Baptism of Vajk'', painting by [[Gyula Bencz<U+00FA>r]]]]
He was born as [[Vajk (given name)|Vajk]],<ref name=Britannica/>{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=27}} which derived from a [[Turkic languages|Turkic]] word ''baj'', meaning "hero", "master", "prince", or "rich".{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=15}}{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=46}} Stephen's ''Greater Legend'' narrates that he was baptized by Bishop [[Adalbert of Prague]],{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=78}} who stayed in G<U+00E9>za's court several times between 983 and 994.{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p=329}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=16}} However, Adalbert's nearly contemporaneous ''Legend'', written by [[Bruno of Querfurt]], does not mention of the event.{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p=329}}{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=78}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=16}}  Accordingly, the date of Stephen's baptism is unknown: Gy<U+00F6>rffy argues that Stephen was baptized soon after birth,{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=78}} while Krist<U+00F3> proposes that he only received baptism just before his father's death in 997.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=16}} He was given his [[baptismal name]] in honour of the first martyr, [[Saint Stephen]].

Stephen's ''Legend'', written by [[Hartvik]], narrates that he "was fully instructed in knowledge of the grammatical art"<ref name=Hartvic>''Hartvic, Life of King Stephen of Hungary'' (ch. 4), p. 381.</ref> in his childhood, implying that he studied [[Latin language|Latin]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=15}} His two other legends do not mention Stephen's grammatical studies. They only state that he "was brought up by receiving an education appropriate for a little prince".{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=15}} Krist<U+00F3> says that the latter remark only refers to Stephen's physical training, including his participation in hunts and military actions.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=15}} According to the ''Illuminated Chronicle'', one of his tutors was a Count Deodatus from [[Kingdom of Italy (imperial)|Italy]], who later founded a monastery in [[Tata, Hungary|Tata]].{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1983|p=132}}

According to Stephen's legends, Grand Prince G<U+00E9>za convoked an assembly of the Hungarian chieftains and warriors when Stephen "ascended to the first stage of adolescence",<ref name=Hartvic/> when he was 14 or 15.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|pp=79-80}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=17}} G<U+00E9>za nominated Stephen as his successor and all those who were present took an oath of loyalty to the young prince.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=17}} Gy<U+00F6>rgy Gy<U+00F6>rffy also writes, without referring to his source, that G<U+00E9>za appointed his son to rule the "[[Principality of Nitra|Nyitra ducate]]" around that time.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=78}} [[Slovaks|Slovak]] historians, including J<U+00E1>n Steinh<U+00FC>bel and J<U+00E1>n Luka<U+010D>ka, accept Gy<U+00F6>rffy's view and propose that Stephen administered [[Nyitra]] (now Nitra, Slovakia) from around 995.{{sfn|Steinh<U+00FC>bel|2011|p=19}}{{sfn|Luka<U+010D>ka|2011|p=31}}

Upon his father's initiative,  Stephen married [[Gisela of Hungary|Gisela]], the daughter of [[Henry the Wrangler]], [[Duke of Bavaria]] (r. 955<U+2013>995) in or after 995.<ref name="Britannica" />{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|pp=16-17}} This marriage established the first family link between a Hungarian ruler and a Western European ruling house,{{sfn|Moln<U+00E1>r|2001|p = 20}} because Gisella was closely related to the [[Ottonian dynasty]] of the [[Holy Roman Emperors]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=16}} According to popular tradition preserved in the [[Scheyern Abbey]] in Bavaria, the ceremony took place at the castle of [[Scheyern]] and was celebrated by Bishop Adalbert of Prague.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=17}} Gisela was accompanied to her new home by [[Bavaria]]n knights, many of whom received land grants from her husband and settled in Hungary.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=81}} The arrival of these heavy-armed warriors strengthened Stephen's military position.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=18}} Gy<U+00F6>rffy writes that Stephen and his wife "presumably" settled in Nyitra after their marriage.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=81}}

==Reign (997<U+2013>1038)==

===Grand Prince (997<U+2013>1000)===
{{see also|Grand Prince of the Hungarians}}
Grand Prince G<U+00E9>za died in 997.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=27}}{{sfn|Luka<U+010D>ka|2011|p=33}} Stephen soon convoked an assembly to Esztergom where his supporters declared him grand prince.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=83}} Initially, he only controlled the northwestern regions of the [[Carpathian Basin]]; the rest of the territory was still dominated by tribal chieftains.<ref name='Krist<U+00F3>_web'>{{cite web |last = Krist<U+00F3> |first = Gyula |title = Kopp<U+00E1>ny lever<U+00E9>se [=Kopp<U+00E1>ny's defeat] |work = Szent Istv<U+00E1>n kir<U+00E1>ly [=King Saint Stephen] |publisher =http://mek.oszk.hu |year =2001 |url =http://mek.oszk.hu/05000/05000/html/kristo013.html | accessdate =2013-08-17}}</ref> Stephen's ascension to the throne was in line with the principle of [[primogeniture]] of Christian monarchies which prescribed that a father was succeeded by his son.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=18}} However, it contradicted the traditional idea of [[seniority]], according to which G<U+00E9>za should have been succeeded by the most senior member of the [[<U+00C1>rp<U+00E1>d dynasty]], who was [[Kopp<U+00E1>ny]] at that time.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=18}}{{sfn|Kontler|1999|pp=52-53}} Kopp<U+00E1>ny, who held the title of duke of [[Somogy County (former)|Somogy]],{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=30}} had for many years administered the regions of [[Transdanubia]] to the south of [[Lake Balaton]].{{sfn|Luka<U+010D>ka|2011|p=33}}{{sfn|Moln<U+00E1>r|2001|p=20}}

Kopp<U+00E1>ny announced his claim to the throne and rebelled against Stephen.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=83}}{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=11}} He also decided to marry G<U+00E9>za's widow, Sarolt, in accordance with the pagan custom of [[levirate marriage]].{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=83}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|pp=18-19}} Although it is not impossible that Kopp<U+00E1>ny had already in 972 been baptized,{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=83}} most of his partisans were pagans, opponents of Christianity represented by Stephen and his predominantly German retinue.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=19}} A charter of 1002 for the [[Pannonhalma Archabbey]] even writes of a war between "the Germans and the Hungarians" when referring to the armed conflicts between Stephen and Kopp<U+00E1>ny.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|pp=83-84}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=19}} Even so, Gy<U+00F6>rffy says that ''Oszlar'' ("[[Alans|Alan]]"), ''Beseny<U+0151>'' ("[[Pechenegs|Pecheneg]]"), ''K<U+00E9>r'' and other place names, referring to ethnic groups or [[Hungarian tribes]] in Transdanubia around the supposed borders of Kopp<U+00E1>ny's duchy, suggest that significant auxiliary units and groups of Hungarian warriors{{mdash}}who had been settled there by Grand Prince G<U+00E9>za{{mdash}}fought in Stephen's army.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=84}}
[[File:Koppany.jpg|thumb|left|190px|alt=Kopp<U+00E1>ny's execution|[[Kopp<U+00E1>ny]]'s execution after his defeat by Stephen]]
Krist<U+00F3> states that the entire conflict between Stephen and Kopp<U+00E1>ny was only a feud between two members of the [[<U+00C1>rp<U+00E1>d dynasty]], with no effect on other Hungarian tribal leaders.<ref name='Krist<U+00F3>_web'/> Kopp<U+00E1>ny and his troops invaded the northern regions of Transdanubia, took many of Stephen's forts and plundered his lands.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=19}} Stephen, who "was for the first time girded with his sword",<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 39.64), p. 105.</ref> placed the brothers [[Hont-P<U+00E1>zm<U+00E1>ny#Notable members of the clan|Hont and P<U+00E1>zm<U+00E1>ny]] at the head of his own guard and nominated [[Vecelin]] to lead the royal army.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|pp=63, 83}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=19}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=39}} The latter was a German knight who had come to Hungary in the reign of G<U+00E9>za.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=63}} Hont and P<U+00E1>zm<U+00E1>ny were, according to [[Simon of K<U+00E9>za]]'s ''[[Gesta Hunnorum et Hungarorum]]'' and the ''Illuminated Chronicle'', "knights of [[Duchy of Swabia|Swabian]] origin"<ref>''Simon of K<U+00E9>za: The Deeds of the Hungarians'' (ch. 78.), p. 163.</ref> who settled in Hungary either under G<U+00E9>za or in the first years of Stephen's reign.<ref name='Krist<U+00F3>_web'/> On the other hand, Luka<U+010D>ka and other Slovak historians say that Hont and P<U+00E1>zm<U+00E1>ny were "Slovak" noblemen who had joined Stephen during his rule in Nyitra.{{sfn|Luka<U+010D>ka|2011|pp=32-33}}

Kopp<U+00E1>ny was besieging [[Veszpr<U+00E9>m]] when he was informed of the arrival of Stephen's army.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=84}} In the battle between Veszpr<U+00E9>m and [[V<U+00E1>rpalota]],{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=84}} Stephen won a decisive victory over his enemies.{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=11}} Kopp<U+00E1>ny himself was killed on the battlefield.{{sfn|Moln<U+00E1>r|2001|p=20}} His body was quartered and its parts were displayed at the gates of the forts of Esztergom, [[Gy<U+0151>r]], [[Gyulafeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r]] (Alba Iulia, [[Romania]]) and Veszpr<U+00E9>m in order to threaten all of those who were conspiring against the young monarch.{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=11}}{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=53}}{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=85}}

Stephen occupied Kopp<U+00E1>ny's duchy and granted large estates to his own partisans.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|pp = 85-86}}{{sfn|Luka<U+010D>ka|2011|p = 33}} According to the [[Interpolation (manuscripts)|interpolated]] deed of the foundation of the Pannonhalma Archabbey,{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p = 351}} he also prescribed that Kopp<U+00E1>ny's former subjects were to pay [[tithe]] to this monastery.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p = 19}} The same document declares that "there were no other bishoprics and monasteries in Hungary" at that time.{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 52}} On the other hand, the nearly contemporary Bishop [[Thietmar of Merseburg]] clearly states that Stephen "established bishoprics in his kingdom"<ref name="Chronicon_193">''The'' Chronicon ''of Thietmar of Merseburg'' (ch. 29.), p. 193.</ref> before being crowned king.{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 52}} If the latter report is valid, the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Veszpr<U+00E9>m|dioceses of Veszpr<U+00E9>m]] and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Gy<U+0151>r|Gy<U+0151>r]] are the most probable candidates.{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|pp = 52-54}}

===Coronation (1000<U+2013>1001)===
{{see also|King of Hungary|Coronation of the Hungarian monarch}}
[[File:Aftnn King Stephen, who we reckon was responsible for Christianity in eastern Europe.jpg|thumb|right|190px|alt=St Stephen's modern sculpture in Budapest|King Saint Stephen's modern sculpture in [[Budapest]]]]
When sending one part of Kopp<U+00E1>ny's quartered corpse to Gyulafeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r, the seat of his maternal uncle, [[Gyula III|Gyula the Younger]], Stephen demonstrated his claim to reign all lands dominated by Hungarian lords.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=20}} He also decided to confirm his international position by adopting the title of king.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=21}} However, the exact circumstances of his coronation and its political consequences are subject to scholarly debate.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=28}}

Thietmar of Merseburg writes that Stephen received the crown "with the favour and urging"<ref name='Chronicon_193'/> of Emperor [[Otto III, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto III]] (r. 996<U+2013>1002),{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p = 343}} implying that Stephen accepted the emperor's suzerainty before his coronation.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p = 28}} On the other hand, all of Stephen's legends emphasize that he received his crown from [[Pope Sylvester II]] (r. 999<U+2013>1003).{{sfn|Engel|2001|p = 28}} Krist<U+00F3>{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=22}} and other historians{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 96}} point out that Pope Sylvester and Emperor Otto were close allies, which implies that both reports are valid: Stephen "received the crown and consecration"<ref name='Chronicon_193'/> from the pope, but not without the emperor's consent. Around 75 years after the coronation, [[Pope Gregory VII]] (r. 1075<U+2013>1085), who claimed suzerainty over Hungary, declared that Stephen had "offered and devotedly surrendered" Hungary "to [[Saint Peter]]" (that is to the [[Holy See]]).<ref>''Pope Gregory VII's letter to King Solomon of Hungary, claiming suzerainty over that kingdom'', p. 48.</ref>{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p = 343}}{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 96}} In a contrasting report, Stephen's ''Greater Legend'' states that the king offered Hungary to the [[Virgin Mary]].{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=96}} Modern historians{{mdash}}including P<U+00E1>l Engel, Gy<U+00F6>rgy Gy<U+00F6>rffy and Mikl<U+00F3>s Moln<U+00E1>r{{mdash}}write that Stephen always demonstrated his sovereignty, which excludes that he ever accepted papal or imperial suzerainty.{{sfn|Moln<U+00E1>r|2001|p=20}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=28}}{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|pp=96-97}} For instance, none of his charters were dated according to the years of the reign of the contemporary emperors, which would have been the case if he had been the German monarch's vassal.{{sfn|Makk|2001|p=45}} Furthermore, Stephen declared in the preamble to his ''First Book of Laws'' that he governed his realm "by the will of God".<ref>''Laws of King Stephen I'' (Stephen I:Preface), p. 1.</ref>{{sfn|Makk|2001|p=45}}

The exact date of Stephen's coronation is unknown.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=22}} According to later Hungarian tradition, he was crowned on the first day of the second millennium, which may refer either to 25 December 1000 or to 1 January 1001.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|pp=22-23}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=27}} Details of Stephen's coronation preserved in his ''Greater Legend'' suggest that the ceremony, which took place in Esztergom, followed the rite of the coronation of the German kings.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=98}} Accordingly, Stephen was [[Anointment|anointed]] with [[chrism|consecrated oil]] during the ceremony.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=98}} Stephen's portrait, preserved on his royal cloak from 1031, proves that his crown, similarly to the Holy Roman Emperor's diadem, was a [[hoop crown]] decorated with [[gemstones]].{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=97}}

Besides his crown, Stephen regarded a spear with a flag as an important symbol of his sovereignty.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=97}} For instance, his first coins bear the inscription LANCEA REGIS ("the king's spear") and depict an arm holding a spear with flag.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=97}} According to the contemporaneous [[Ad<U+00E9>mar de Chabannes]], a spear had been given to Stephen's father by Emperor Otto III in a token of G<U+00E9>za's right to "enjoy the most freedom in the possession of his country".{{sfn|Makk|2001|p=41}} Stephen is styled in various ways{{mdash}}''Ungarorum rex'' ("king of the Hungarians"), ''Pannoniorum rex'' ("king of the Pannonians") or ''Hungarie rex'' ("king of Hungary"){{mdash}}in his charters.{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p=343}}

===Consolidation (1001<U+2013>c. 1009)===
Although Stephen's power did not rely on his coronation,{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p=343}} the ceremony granted him the internationally accepted legitimacy of a Christian monarch who ruled his realm "[[by the Grace of God]]".{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=23}} All his legends testify that he established an [[Archdiocese of Esztergom|archbishopric with its see in Esztergom]] shortly after his coronation.{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 54}} This act ensured that the Church in Hungary became independent of the prelates of the Holy Roman Empire.{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 53}}{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p= 54}} The earliest reference to an archbishop of Esztergom, named [[Domonkos I, Archbishop of Esztergom|Domokos]], has been preserved in the deed of foundation of the Pannonhalma Archabbey from 1002.{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 54}} According to Thoroczkay, Stephen also established the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Kalocsa-Kecskem<U+00E9>t|Diocese of Kalocsa]] in 1001.{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 58}} Stephen invited foreign priests to Hungary to evangelize his kingdom.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p= 54}} Associates of the late Adalbert of Prague, including [[Radla]] and [[Astrik]], arrived in Hungary in the first years of his reign.{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p=336}}{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|pp = 55-57}}

The transformation of Hungary into a Christian state was one of Stephen's principal concerns throughout his reign.{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=14}} His legislative activity was closely connected with Christianity.{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p=333}} For example, his ''First Book of Laws'' from the first years of his reign includes several provisions prescribing the observance of [[feast day]]s and the [[Sacrament of Penance (Catholic Church)|confession]] before death.{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p=334}}{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 135}} His other laws protected property rights{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=15}} and the interests of widows and orphans, or regulated the status of serfs.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 135}}

{{Quote|If someone has such a hardened heart{{mdash}}God forbid it to any Christian{{mdash}}that he does not want to confess his faults according to the counsel of a priest, he shall lie without any divine service and alms like an infidel. If his relatives and neighbors fail to summon the priest, and therefore he should die unconfessed, prayers and alms should be offered, but his relatives shall wash away their negligence by [[Fasting and abstinence in the Roman Catholic Church|fasting]] in accordance with the judgement of the priests. Those who die a sudden death shall be buried with all ecclesiastical honor; for divine judgment is hidden from us and unknown.''|''Laws of King Stephen I<ref>''Laws of King Stephen I'' (Stephen I:12), p. 4.</ref>}}

[[File:Stephen's forces capture Gyula.png|thumb|left|190px|alt=Gyula the Younger is captured|Stephen's forces seize his uncle, [[Gyula III|Gyula the Younger]]]]
Many Hungarian lords refused to accept Stephen's suzerainty even after his coronation.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p = 53}} The new king first turned against his own uncle, Gyula the Younger, whose realm "was most wide and rich",<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 40.65), p. 105.</ref> according to the ''Illuminated Chronicle''.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p = 24}} Stephen invaded Transylvania and seized Gyula and his family around 1002{{sfn|S<U+0103>l<U+0103>gean|2005|pp = 150-151}}{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=145}} or in 1003.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p = 27}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p = 24}} The contemporary ''Annals of Hildesheim''{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=145}} adds that Stephen converted his uncle's "country to the Christian faith by force" after its conquest.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p = 24}} Accordingly, historians date the establishment of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Alba Iulia|Diocese of Translyvania]] to this period.{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=145}}{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 58}} If the identification, proposed by Krist<U+00F3>, Gy<U+00F6>rffy and other Hungarian historians, of Gyula with one Prokui{{mdash}}who was Stephen's uncle according to Thietmar of Merseburg{{mdash}}is valid,{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=146}} Gyula later escaped from captivity and fled to [[Boleslav the Brave]], [[Duke of Poland]] (r. 992<U+2013>1025).{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p = 24}}

{{Quote|[Duke Boleslav the Brave's] territory included a certain burg, located near the border with the Hungarians. Its guardian was lord Prokui, an uncle of the Hungarian king. Both in the past and more recently, Prokui had been driven from his lands by the king and his wife had been taken captive. When he was unable to free her, his nephew arranged for her unconditional release, even though he was Prokui's enemy. I have never heard of anyone who showed such restraint towards a defeated foe. Because of this, God repeatedly granted him victory, not only in the burg mentioned above, but in others as well.|[[Thietmar of Merseburg]]: ''Chronicum''<ref>''The'' Chronicon ''of Thietmar of Merseburg'' (ch. 8.4), pp. 363-364.</ref>}}

About a hundred years later the chronicler [[Gallus Anonymus]] also made mention of armed conflicts between Stephen and Boleslav the Brave, by stating that the latter "defeated the Hungarians in battle and made himself master of all their lands as far as the [[Danube]]".<ref>''The Deeds of the Princes of the Poles'' (ch. 6.), pp. 31-33.</ref>{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 142}}{{sfn|Steinh<U+00FC>bel|2011|p= 19}} Gy<U+00F6>rffy says that the chronicler's report refers to the occupation of the valley of the river [[Morava (river)|Morava]] by the [[Poles]] in the 1010s.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 142}} On the other hand, the ''[[Polish-Hungarian Chronicle]]'' states that the Polish duke occupied large territories north of the Danube as far as Esztergom in the early 1000s.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 142}}{{sfn|Steinh<U+00FC>bel|2011|pp= 19-21}} According to Steinh<U+00FC>bel, the latter source proves that a significant part of the lands that now form Slovakia were under Polish rule between 1002 and 1030.{{sfn|Steinh<U+00FC>bel|2011|pp= 19-21}} In contrast with the Slovak historian, Gy<U+00F6>rffy writes that this late chronicle "in which one absurdity follows another" contradicts all facts known from 11th-century sources.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|pp= 107-108, 142}}
[[File:Istv<U+00E1>nkir<U+00E1>ly.jpg|thumb|right|190px|alt=Kean's defeat by Stephen|Stephen defeats Kean "Duke of the Bulgarians and Slavs"]]
The ''Illuminated Chronicle'' narrates that Stephen "led his army against Kean, Duke of the Bulgarians and Slavs whose lands are by their natural position most strongly fortified"<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 41.66), p. 105.</ref> following the occupation of Gyula's country.{{sfn|Lenkey|2003|p= 37}} According to a number of historians, including Zolt<U+00E1>n Lenkey{{sfn|Lenkey|2003|p= 37}} and G<U+00E1>bor Thoroczkay,{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 58}} Kean was the head of a small state located in the southern parts of Transylvania and Stephen occupied his country around 1003. Other historians, including Gy<U+00F6>rffy, say that the chronicle's report preserved the memory of Stephen's campaign against [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgaria]] in the late 1010s.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 91}}

Likewise, the identification of the "[[Black Hungarians]]"<ref>''Life of the Five Brethren by Bruno of Querfurt'' (ch. 10.), p. 245.</ref>{{mdash}}who were mentioned by Bruno of Querfurt and Ad<U+00E9>mar de Chabannes among the opponents of Stephen's proselytizing policy{{mdash}}is uncertain.{{sfn|Lenkey|2003|pp= 38-39}} Gy<U+00F6>rffy locates their lands to the east of the river [[Tisza]],{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 187}} while Thoroczkay to the southern parts of Transdanubia.{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 58}} Bruno of Querfurt's report of the Black Hungarians' conversion by force suggests that Stephen conquered their lands at the latest in 1009 when "the first mission of Saint Peter"{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 60}}{{mdash}}a [[papal legate]], Cardinal Azo{{mdash}}arrived in Hungary.{{sfn|Lenkey|2003|p= 39}} The latter attended the meeting in [[Gy<U+0151>r]] where the royal charter determining the borders of the newly established [[Roman Catholic Diocese of P<U+00E9>cs|Bishopric of P<U+00E9>cs]] was issued on August 23, 1009.{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 60}}

The  [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Eger|Diocese of Eger]] was also set up around 1009.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 108}}{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 60}} According to Thoroczkay, "it is very probable" that the bishopric's establishment was connected with the conversion of the [[Kabars]]{{mdash}}an ethnic group of [[Khazars|Khazar]] origin{{mdash}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p = 22}} and their chieftain.{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 61}} The head of the Kavars{{mdash}}who was either [[Samuel Aba]] or his father{{mdash}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p = 29}} married Stephen's unnamed younger sister on this occasion.{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 61}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p = 63}} The [[Aba (family)|Aba clan]] was the most powerful among the native families who joined Stephen and supported him in his efforts to establish a Christian monarchy.{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp = 40, 85}} The reports by [[Anonymus (chronicler)|Anonymous]], Simon of K<U+00E9>za and other Hungarian chroniclers of the B<U+00E1>r-Kal<U+00E1>n, [[Cs<U+00E1>k (genus)|Cs<U+00E1>k]] and other 13th-century noble families descending from Hungarian chieftains prove that other native families were also involved in the process.{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp = 40, 85}}

Stephen abolished tribal divisions{{sfn|Butler|Cumming|Burns|1998|pp=159-160}} and set up a territory-based administrative system,{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p = 24}} establishing [[Counties of the Kingdom of Hungary|counties]].{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp= 40-41}} Each county, headed a by royal official known as a count or ''[[isp<U+00E1>n]]'', were administrative units organized around royal fortresses.{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp= 40-41}} Most fortresses were earthworks in this period,{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 119}} but the castles at Esztergom, [[Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r]] and Veszpr<U+00E9>m were built of stone.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p= 41}} Forts serving as county seats also became the nuclei of Church organization.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 119}} The settlements developing around them, where markets were held on each Sunday, were important local economic centers.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 119}}

===Active foreign policy (c. 1009<U+2013>1031)===
[[Image:IstvanKiraly sculpture miskolc.jpg|190px|thumb|A statue of the king in [[Miskolc]]]]
Stephen's brother-in-law, [[Henry II, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry II]], became [[King of Germany]] in 1002 and Holy Roman Emperor in 1013.{{sfn|Makk|2001|p=45}} Their friendly relationship ensured that the Western borders of Hungary experienced a period of peace in the first decades of the 11th&nbsp;century.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 140}}{{sfn|Makk|2001|p=45}} Even when Henry II's discontented brother, [[Bruno of Augsburg|Bruno]], sought refugee in Hungary in 1004, Stephen preserved the peace with Germany and negotiated a settlement between his two brothers-in-law.{{sfn|Makk|2001|p=45}}{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 133}}  Around 1009, he gave his younger sister in marriage to [[Otto Orseolo]], [[Doge of Venice]] (r. 1008<U+2013>1026), a close ally of the [[Byzantine Emperor]], [[Basil II]] (r. 976<U+2013>1025), which suggests that Hungary's relationship with the [[Byzantine Empire]] was also peaceful.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 144}}

On the other hand, the alliance between Hungary and the Holy Roman Empire brought Hungary into a war with Poland lasting from around 1014{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2003|p= 71}} until 1018.{{sfn|Lenkey|2003|p= 88}} The Poles occupied the Hungarian posts along the river Morava.{{sfn|Makk|1993|pp=48-49}} Gy<U+00F6>rffy and Krist<U+00F3> write that a [[Pechenegs|Pecheneg]] incursion into Transylvania, the memory of which has been preserved in Stephen's legends, also took place in this period, because the Pechenegs were close allies of Boleslav the Brave's brother-in-law, Grand Prince [[Sviatopolk I of Kiev]] (r. 1015<U+2013>1019).{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2003|p= 71}}{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 143}} However, 500 Hungarian horsemen who accompanied Boleslav the Brave to [[Kiev]] already in 1018 indicate that Hungary had been included in the [[Peace of Bautzen]] between Poland and the Holy Roman Empire.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 143}} The historian Ferenc Makk says that the peace treaty obliged Boleslav the Brave to hand over all the territories he had occupied in the Morava valley to Stephen.{{sfn|Makk|1993|pp=48-49}}

{{Quote|For some night suddenly awakaned by some [[revelation]],'' [Stephen] ''ordered a courier to hasten in one day and night to [[Gyulafeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r|Alba in Transylvania]], and gather all those living in the country within the fortifications of the city as fast as he could. For he foretold that the enemies of Christians would come upon them, the Pechenegs, who then threatened the Hungarians, in order to plunder their estate. Scarcely had the messenger completed the orders of the king, when behold the unexpected onslaught of the Pechenegs devastated everything by burning and plundering. Through the revelation of God, which was granted because of the merits of the blessed man, the souls of everyone were saved by the shelter of the fortifications.|''[[Hartvik|Hartvic]], Life of King Stephen of Hungary''<ref>''Hartvic, Life of King Stephen of Hungary'' (ch. 16.), p. 388.</ref>}}

According to Leodvin, the first known [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Oradea Mare|Bishop of Bihar]] (r. c. 1050 <U+2013> c. 1060), Stephen allied with the Byzantines and made a military expedition in order to assist them against "[[barbarian]]s" in the [[Balkan Peninsula]].{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|pp= 145-146}} The Byzantine and Hungarian troops jointly took "Cesaries", a town identified with [[Ohrid]] by Gy<U+00F6>rffy{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 146}} and other historians. Here, Stephen collected [[relic]]s of a number of saints, including [[Saint George]] and [[Saint Nicholas of Myra]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2003|p= 72}} Leodvin's report suggests that Stephen intervened in the war ending with the [[Byzantine conquest of Bulgaria]] in 1018.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2003|p= 72}} However, the exact date of his expedition is uncertain.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 146}} Gy<U+00F6>rffy argues that it was only in the last year of the war that Stephen led his troops against the Bulgarians, because in the previous years he had fought against the Poles.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p= 146}}
[[File:CivertanPecsvarad.jpg|thumb|left|190px|alt=P<U+00E9>csv<U+00E1>rad Abbey|Ruins of the [[P<U+00E9>csv<U+00E1>rad Abbey]]]]
Stephen donated the relics acquired in Cesaries to his triple-naved, new basilica dedicated to the Holy Virgin{{sfn|Butler|Cumming|Burns|1998|p=159}} in Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|pp= 146, 151}} He also set up a [[cathedral chapter]] here.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p= 43}} Stephen transferred his seat from Esztergom to Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r. His decision was not independent of the opening, in 1018 or 1019, of a new [[pilgrimage]] route, connecting Western Europe and the [[Holy Land]] through Hungary, while bypassing his old seat.{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=16}}{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|pp= 147, 151}} Stephen often met the pilgrims, contributing to the spread of his fame throughout Europe.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 148}} Abbot [[Odilo of Cluny]], for example, wrote in his letter to Stephen that "those who have returned from the [[Church of the Holy Sepulchre|shrine of our Lord]]" testify to the king's passion "towards the honour of our divine religion".{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 147}} Stephen himself also established four hostels for pilgrims in Constantinople, [[Jerusalem]], [[Ravenna]] and [[Rome]].{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 150}}

In addition to pilgrims, merchants often used the safe route across Hungary when travelling between Constantinople and Western Europe.{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=16}} Stephen's legends also write of 60 wealthy Pechenegs who travelled to Hungary, but were attacked by Hungarian border guards.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=28}} The king sentenced his soldiers to death in order to demonstrate his determination to preserve internal peace.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=28}} Regular minting also began in Hungary in the 1020s.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 160}} Stephen's silver dinars{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=16}} bearing the inscriptions STEPHANUS REX ("King Stephen") and REGIA CIVITAS ("royal city") were popular in contemporary Europe, as demonstrated by their conterfeited copies unearthed in [[Sweden]].{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 160}}
[[File:Szekesfehervar Puspokkut3.jpg|thumb|right|190px|alt=Saints Gerard and Emeric|Modern statute of Bishop [[Gerard Sagredo|Gerard of Csan<U+00E1>d]] and his disciple, Prince [[Emeric of Hungary|Emeric]] (both were canonized along with King Stephen in 1083)]]
Stephen convinced some pilgrims and merchants to settle in Hungary.{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=16}}{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 147}} [[Gerard Sagredo|Gerard]], a member of the Sagredo or [[Morosini family]],{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 63}} who arrived in Hungary  from the [[Republic of Venice]] between 1020 and 1026 initially planned to continue his journey to the Holy Land, but decided to stay in the country after his meeting with the king.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 148}} Stephen also established a number of Benedictine monasteries{{mdash}}including the abbeys at [[P<U+00E9>csv<U+00E1>rad Abbey|P<U+00E9>csv<U+00E1>rad]], [[Zalav<U+00E1>r]] and [[Bakonyb<U+00E9>l Abbey|Bakonyb<U+00E9>l]]{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p = 352}}{{mdash}}in this period.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 110}}

Stephen's brother-in-law, Emperor Henry, died on 13 July 1024.{{sfn|Wolfram|2006|p = 40}} He was succeeded by a distant relative,{{sfn|Wolfram|2006|p = 187}} [[Conrad II, Holy Roman Emperor|Conrad II]] (r. 1024<U+2013>1039), who adopted an active foreign policy.{{sfn|Lenkey|2003|p = 90}} Conrad II expelled Doge Otto Orseolo{{mdash}}the husband of Stephen's sister{{mdash}}from Venice in 1026.{{sfn|Lenkey|2003|p = 90}}{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 148}} He also persuaded the Bavarians to proclaim his own son, [[Henry III, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry]], as their duke in 1027, although Stephen's son, Emeric had a strong claim to the [[Duchy of Bavaria]] through his mother.{{sfn|Wolfram|2006|p = 187}}

Emperor Conrad planned a marriage alliance with the Byzantine Empire and dispatched one of his advisors, Bishop [[Werner I (Bishop of Strasbourg)|Werner of Strasbourg]], to Constantinople.{{sfn|Butler|Cumming|Burns|1998|p=159}}{{sfn|Wolfram|2006|pp = 197-198}} The bishop seemingly travelled as a pilgrim, but Stephen, who had been informed on his actual purpose, refused to let him enter into his country in the autumn of 1027.{{sfn|Butler|Cumming|Burns|1998|p=159}}{{sfn|Wolfram|2006|pp = 197-198}} Conrad II's biographer, [[Wipo of Burgundy]] narrated that the Bavarians incited skirmishes along the common borders of Hungary and the Holy Roman Empire in 1029, causing a rapid deterioration in relations between the two countries.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 149}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2003|p = 74}}

Stephen's conflict with [[Ajtony]], a chieftain in the region of the river [[Mure<U+0219> River|Maros]]{{mdash}}which is narrated in the ''Long Life of Saint Gerard''{{mdash}}is also dated by many historians to the very end of the 1020s, although Gy<U+00F6>rffy{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 142}} and other scholars wrote that it happened at least a decade earlier.{{sfn|Curta|2001|p = 40}} The conflict arose when Ajtony, who "had taken his power from the Greeks", levied tax on the salt transported to Stephen on the river.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 101}} The king sent a large army led by [[Csan<U+00E1>d]] against Ajtony, who was killed in a battle.{{sfn|Curta|2001|p = 142}} His lands were transformed into a [[Csan<U+00E1>d County|county]] and the king set up a [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Szeged-Csan<U+00E1>d|new bishopric at Csan<U+00E1>d]] (Cenad, Romania), the former seat of Ajtony, which was renamed after the commander of the royal army.{{sfn|Curta|2001|p = 142}} According to the ''[[Annales Posonienses]]'', the Venetian Gerard was consecrated as the first bishop of the new diocese in 1030.{{sfn|Thoroczkay|2001|p = 62}}

Emperor Conrad personally led his armies to Hungary in June 1030 and plundered the lands west of the river [[R<U+00E1>ba]].{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 149}}{{sfn|Wolfram|2006|p = 231}} However, as the ''Annals of Niederalteich'' reported it, the emperor, suffering from consequences of the [[scorched earth]] tactics applied by the Hungarian army,{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2003|pp = 74-75}} returned to Germany "without an army and without achieving anything, because the army was threatened by starvation and was captured by the Hungarians at [[Vienna]]".{{sfn|Wolfram|2006|p = 231}} The peace was restored after Conrad had ceded the lands between the rivers [[Lajta]] and [[Fischa]] to Hungary in the summer of 1031.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|pp = 149-150}}

{{Quote|At this same time, dissensions arose between the Pannonian nation and the Bavarians, through the fault of the Bavarians. And, as a result, King'' [Stephen] ''of Hungary made many incursions and raids in the realm of the Norici (that is, of the Bavarians). Disturbed on this account Emperor Conrad came upon the Hungarians with a great army. But King'' [Stephen]'', whose forces were entirely insufficient to meet the Emperor, relled solely on the guardianship of the Lord, which he sought with prayers and fasts proclaimed through his whole realm. Since the Emperor was not able to enter a kingdom so [[gyep<U+00FC>|fortified with rivers and forests]], he returned, after he had sufficiently avenged his injury with lootings and burnings on the borders of the kingdom; and it was his wish at a more opportune time to complete the things he had begun. His son, King [[Henry III, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry]], however, still a young boy entrusted to the care of Eigilbert, [[bishop of Freising]], received a legation of King'' [Stephen] ''which asked for peace; and solely with the counsel of the princes of the realm, and without his father's knowledge, he granted the favor of reconciliation.|[[Wipo of Burgundy|Wipo]]: ''The Deeds of Conrad II''<ref>''The Deeds of Conrad II (Wipo)'' (ch. 26.), pp. 85-86.</ref>}}

===Last years (1031<U+2013>1038)===
[[File:Imrich stepan.jpg|190px|thumb|right|alt=King St Stephen and his son|King Stephen at the funeral of his son, [[Saint Emeric of Hungary|Saint Emeric]]]]
Stephen's biographer, Hartvic narrates that the king, whose children died one by one in infancy, "restrained the grief over their death by the solace on account of the love of his surviving son",<ref>''Hartvic, Life of King Stephen of Hungary'' (ch. 19), p. 390.</ref> [[Saint Emeric of Hungary|Emeric]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=48}} However, Emeric was wounded in a hunting accident and died in 1031.{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=16}} After the death of his son, the elderly king could never "fully regain his former health",<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 45.69), p. 107.</ref> according to the ''Illuminated Chronicle''.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=48}} Krist<U+00F3> writes that the picture, which has been preserved in Stephen's legends, of the holy king keeping the [[vigils]] and washing the feet of paupers, is connected with Stephen's last years, following the death of his son.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=32}}

Emeric's death jeopardized his father's achievements in establishing a Christian state,{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=169}} because Stephen's cousin, [[Vazul]]{{mdash}}who had the strongest claim to succeede him{{mdash}}was suspected to incline toward paganism.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|pp=58-59}} The ''[[Annales Altahenses|Annals of Altaich]]'' narrated that Stephen disregarded his cousin's claim and nominated his own sister's son, the Venetian [[Peter Orseolo]] as his heir.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=170}} The same source adds that Vazul was captured and blinded; his three sons, [[Levente]], [[Andrew I of Hungary|Andrew]] and [[B<U+00E9>la I of Hungary|B<U+00E9>la]], were expelled from Hungary.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=170}} A report, preserved in Stephen's legends, of an unsuccessful attempt upon the elderly king's life by members of his court indicate that Vazul was mutilated for his participation in the plot.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=32}} That Vazul's ears were filled with molten lead was only recorded in later sources, including the ''Illuminated Chronicle''.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|pp=169-170}}

Provisions in Stephen's ''Second Book of Laws'' on the "conspiracy against the king and the kingdom"<ref>''Laws of King Stephen I'' (Stephen II:19), p. 11.</ref> implies that this book was promulgated after Vazul's unsuccessful plot against Stephen.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=135}} However, historians have not universally accepted this view.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=135}} Gy<U+00F6>rffy wrote that the law book was issued, not after 1031, but around 1009.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=136}} Likewise, the authenticity of Stephen's decree on the tithe is debated: according to Gy<U+00F6>rffy, it is duly attributed to Stephen, but Berend, Laszlovszky and Szak<U+00E1>cs wrote that it "might be a later addition".{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=136}}{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p=351}}

{{Quote|''Ten villages shall build a church and endow it with two [[manse]]s and the same number of [[bondmen]], a horse and mare, six oxen, two cows, and thirty small animals. The king shall provide vestments and [[altar cloth]]s, and the bishop the priests and books.''|''Laws of King Stephen I''<ref>''Laws of King Stephen I'' (Stephen II:1), p. 9.</ref>}}

Stephen died on 15 August 1038.{{sfn|Guiley|2001|p=136}} He was buried in the basilica of Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=170}} A long period of instability followed his reign, which was characterized by civil wars, pagan uprisings and foreign invasions.{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp=29-32}}{{sfn|Moln<U+00E1>r|2001|pp=25-27}} The period ended in 1077 when [[Ladislaus I of Hungary|Ladislaus]], a grandson of Vazul, ascended the throne.{{sfn|Moln<U+00E1>r|2001|p=27}}

==Family==
[[File:Chronicon Pictum P042 <U+00D3>budai templom alap<U+00ED>t<U+00E1>sa.JPG|thumb|right|alt=King St Stephen and his wife|King Stephen and his wife [[Gisela of Hungary|Gisela of Bavaria]] founding a church at [[<U+00D3>buda]] from the ''[[Chronicon Pictum]]'']]
Stephen married [[Gisela of Hungary|Gisela]], a daughter of Duke Henry the Wrangler of Bavaria{{mdash}}himself a nephew of [[Otto I, Holy Roman Emperor]]{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=26}}{{mdash}}and his wife, [[Gisela of Burgundy]], a member of the [[Elder House of Welf|Welf dynasty]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=17}}{{sfn|Veszpr<U+00E9>my|1994|p=236}} Born around 985, Gisela was younger than her husband, whom she survived.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=17}}{{sfn|Veszpr<U+00E9>my|1994|p=236}} She abandoned Hungary in 1045 and died as Abbess of the Niedernburg Abbey in [[Passau]] in Bavaria around 1060.{{sfn|Veszpr<U+00E9>my|1994|p=237}}

Although the ''Illuminated Chronicle'' narrates that Stephen "begot many sons",<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 38.63), p. 104.</ref>{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=168}} only two of them, Otto and Emeric, are known by name.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=23}} According to Krist<U+00F3>, Otto was born before 1002 and was named after Emperor Otto III.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=23}} He died as a child.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=168}}

[[Saint Emeric of Hungary|Emeric]] who received the name of his maternal uncle, Emperor Henry II, was born around 1007.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p = 23}} His ''Legend'' from the early 1100s describes Emeric as a saintly prince who preserved his [[chastity]] even during his marriage.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 168}} According to Gy<U+00F6>rffy, Emeric's wife was a kinswoman of the Byzantine Emperor Basil II.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p = 146}} His premature death caused the series of conflicts leading to Vazul's blinding and civil wars.{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p = 16}}{{sfn|Butler|Cumming|Burns|1998|p = 160}}

{{Quote|Be obedient to me, my son. You are a child, descendant of rich parents, living among soft pillows, who has been caressed and brought up in all kinds of comforts; you have had a part neither in the troubles of the campaigns nor in the various attacks of the pagans in which almost my whole life has been worn away.|Stephen's ''Admonitions'' to his son, Emeric{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|2001|p=28}}}}

The following family tree presents Stephen's ancestors and his relatives who are mentioned in the article.{{sfn|Veszpr<U+00E9>my|1994|p=236}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|pp=17, Appendices 1-2}}{{sfn|Veszpr<U+00E9>my|1994|p=236}}

