''*A Khazar, Pecheneg or Volga Bulgarian lady.''<br/>**Samuel Aba might have been the son of Stephen's sister instead of her husband.

==Legacy==

===Founder of Hungary===
[[File:Istvan-ChroniconPictum.jpg|190px|thumb|right|alt=King St Stephen in the Illuminated Chronicle|A miniature of King Saint Stephen from the ''[[Illuminated Chronicle]]'']]
Stephen has always been considered one of the most important statesmen in the history of Hungary.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=51}} His main achievement was the establishment of a Christian state which ensured that the Hungarians have survived in the Carpathian Basin, in contrast with the [[Huns]], [[Eurasian Avars|Avars]] and other peoples who had before them controlled the same territory.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=51}} Stephen, as Bryan Cartledge emphasizes, also gave his kingdom "forty years of relative peace and sound but unspectacular rule".{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=17}}

His successors, even those who were descended from Vazul, were eager to emphasize their devotion to Stephen's achievements.{{sfn|Lenkey|2003|p=106}} Vazul's son, [[Andrew I of Hungary]] (r. 1046<U+2013>1060), although he acquired the throne due to a [[Vata pagan uprising|pagan uprising]], prohibited pagan rites and declared that all of his subjects should "live in all things according to the law which King St. Stephen had tought them"<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 60.86), p. 113.</ref> following his coronation.{{sfn|Lenkey|2003|p=106}} In [[Kingdom of Hungary (1000<U+2013>1526)|medieval Hungary]], communities which claimed a privileged status or attempted to preserve their own "[[Privilege (law)|liberties]]" often declared that the origin of their special status was to be attributed to King Saint Stephen.{{sfn|Tringli|2001|p=129}} In a letter of 1347, for example, in their grievances against the Pannonhalma Archabbey to the king, the people of [[T<U+00E1>p]] stated that taxes levied upon them by the Abbot contradicted "the liberty granted to them in the time of King Saint Stephen".{{sfn|Tringli|2001|p=139}}

===The Holy King===
{{Infobox saint
|name=Saint Stephen
|birth_date=''c''. 975
|death_date=15 August 1038
|feast_day=16 August<br/>20 August (in Hungary)<br/>30 May (his Holy Dexter in Hungary)
|venerated_in=[[Roman Catholic Church]]<br/>[[Eastern Orthodox Church]]
|image=Image:St. Stephen, Esztergom.jpg
|imagesize=190px
|caption=
|birth_place=[[Esztergom]], [[Principality of Hungary|Hungary]]
|death_place=[[Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r]], [[Kingdom of Hungary (1000<U+2013>1526)|Hungary]]
|titles=King and Confessor
|beatified_date=
|beatified_place=
|beatified_by=
|canonized_date=20 August 1083
|canonized_place=[[Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r]]
|canonized_by=[[Pope Gregory VII]]
|attributes=[[Crown of St. Stephen|Crown]]; [[Sceptre]]; [[Globus cruciger|globe]]
|patronage=Patron saint of Hungary<br/>Patron of kings, masons, stonecutters, stonemasons and bricklayers<br/>Protector against child death
|major_shrine=[[Saint Stephen's Basilica]] in [[Budapest]], Hungary
|suppressed_date=
|issues=
}}
Stephen's cult emerged after the long period of anarchy  characterizing the rule of his immediate successors.<ref name='Di<U+00F3>s'>{{cite web |last=Di<U+00F3>s |first=Istv<U+00E1>n |title=Szent Istv<U+00E1>n kir<U+00E1>ly [=King Saint Stephen]  |work=A szentek <U+00E9>lete [=Lives of Saints] |publisher=Szent Istv<U+00E1>n t<U+00E1>rsulat |date= |url=http://www.katolikus.hu/szentek/0820.html |accessdate=2013-08-18}}</ref> His tomb at Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r became a popular [[shrine]]<ref name='Di<U+00F3>s'/> where healing miracles were said to have occurred.{{sfn|Butler|Cumming|Burns|1998|p=160}}{{sfn|Guiley|2001|p=314}} King [[Ladislaus I of Hungary]] (r. 1077<U+2013>1095){{mdash}}although himself a grandson of Prince Vazul, who had been blinded on Stephen's orders{{mdash}}initiated his canonization,{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=33}} which was permitted by Pope Gregory VII.{{sfn|Guiley|2001|p=314}} The ceremony started at Stephen's tomb, where masses of believers spent three days fasting and praying from 15 August 1083.{{sfn|Klaniczay|2002|p=124}} Legend says that Stephen's coffin could not be opened until King Ladislaus held his dethroned cousin, [[Solomon of Hungary|Solomon]], in captivity in a prison at [[Visegr<U+00E1>d]].{{sfn|Klaniczay|2002|p=124}} Stephen's "balsam-scented" remains were elevated from the coffin, which was filled with "rose-colored water", on 20 August.{{sfn|Klaniczay|2002|p=124}} On the same day, Stephen's son, Emeric, and the holy bishop of Csan<U+00E1>d, Gerard, were also canonized.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=33}}

{{Quote|A certain youth, all his limbs weakened, suffering paralysis for twelfe years who was without the use of his hands and feet, who was carried there with the aid of his parents, having received the cure of all his body, was the first of the signs. Running to the altar far from sluggishly, he increased the joy of all those shouting praises to Christ.|''[[Hartvik|Hartvic]], Life of King Stephen of Hungary''<ref>''Hartvic, Life of King Stephen of Hungary'' (ch. 25.), p. 394.</ref>}}

Stephen's first legend, the so-called ''Greater Legend'', was written between 1077 and 1083.{{sfn|Berend|2001|p=375}} It provided an idealized portrait of the king,{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=90}} who dedicated himself and his kingdom to the Virgin Mary.{{sfn|Berend|2001|p=375}} However, Stephen's ''Lesser Legend''{{mdash}}which was composed around 1100,{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=90}} under King [[Coloman of Hungary|Coloman]] (r. 1095<U+2013>1116){{sfn|Berend|2001|p=375}}{{mdash}}emphasized Stephen's severity, with Gy<U+00F6>rffy's words, "in an unlegendary way".{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=90}} Stephen's third legend was composed, also in King Coloman's reign, by Bishop [[Hartvik]], who based his text on the previous two legends.{{sfn|Berend|2001|p=375}} Sanctioned in 1201 by [[Pope Innocent III]], Hartvik's work served as Stephen's official legend.{{sfn|Berend|2001|p=375}}

G<U+00E1>bor Klaniczay writes that Stephen's legends, suggesting that a monarch can achieve sainthood through actively using his royal powers, "opened a new chapter in the legends of holy rulers as a genre".{{sfn|Klaniczay|2002|p=136}} Stephen was the first triumphant ''miles Christi'' ("Christ's soldier") among the canonized monarchs.{{sfn|Klaniczay|2002|p=134}} He was also a "confessor king" whose cult was sanctioned, in contrast with earlier holy monarchs, without suffering martyrdom.{{sfn|Klaniczay|2002|p=16}}

Stephen's cult spread beyond the borders of Hungary.<ref name='Di<U+00F3>s'/> Initially he was primarily venerated in Scheyern and [[Bamberg]] in Bavaria, but his relics were also taken to [[Aachen]], [[Cologne]], [[Montecassino]] and [[Namur, Belgium|Namur]].<ref name='Di<U+00F3>s'/> Upon the liberation of Buda from the Ottoman Turks, [[Pope Innocent XI]] expanded Stephen's cult to the entire Roman Catholic Church in 1686.<ref name='Di<U+00F3>s'/> He declared 2 September as King Saint Stephen's [[feast day]].{{sfn|Butler|Cumming|Burns|1998|p=160}}<ref name='Di<U+00F3>s'/> As the feast of Saint [[Joachim]] was moved, in 1969, from 16 August,<ref>"Calendarium Romanum" (Libreria Editrice Vaticana 1969), pp. 98 and 135</ref> the day immediately following the day of Stephen's death, the latter's feast was moved to that date.<ref>"Calendarium Romanum" (Libreria Editrice Vaticana, 1969), pp. 100, 137</ref> Stephen is venerated as the patron saint of Hungary.<ref name='Di<U+00F3>s'/> He also protects kings, masons, stonecutters, stonemasons and bricklayers.{{sfn|Guiley|2001|p=314}} He is the protector of children suffering from serious illnesses menacing their lives.{{sfn|Guiley|2001|p=314}} The canonization of Saint Stephen was recognized by [[Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew I of Constantinople]] in the year 2000.<ref name=Uj_Ember>{{cite journal |last =Papp |first =Tam<U+00E1>s |title =Az ortodox egyh<U+00E1>z is szentk<U+00E9>nt tiszteli: Orsz<U+00E1>galap<U+00ED>t<U+00F3> kir<U+00E1>lyunk <U+00E9>s a keleti hagyom<U+00E1>nyok kapcsolat<U+00E1>r<U+00F3>l [=Venerated also by the Orthodox Church: On the connections between our king founding our state and the Oriental traditions] |journal = <U+00DA>j Ember |volume = 34-35. |issue =LXI |pages =  |publisher =Magyar Katolikus Egyh<U+00E1>z |location = Budapest |date = 2005-08-21 |language = Hungarian |url =http://ujember.katolikus.hu/Archivum/2005.08.21/0201.html |issn = 1418-1657 | accessdate = 2013-08-19}}</ref> In the calendar of the Hungarian Roman Catholic Church, the feast is observed on 20 August, the day on which his relics were [[translation (relics)|translated]].<ref name='Di<U+00F3>s'/> In Hungary, a separate feast day (30 May) is dedicated to Stephen's "Holy Dexter".<ref name='Di<U+00F3>s'/>

===His Holy Dexter===
[[Image:Sztjobb.jpg|190px|right|thumb|alt=St Stephen's intact right hand|The Holy Dexter: King St. Stephen's intact right hand]]
Stephen's intact right hand ({{lang-hu|Szent Jobb}}) became the subject of a cult after it was miraculously found when his tomb was opened in 1083.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=33}}{{sfn|Csorba|2004|p=7}} In [[Bihar County]], an abbey was dedicated to its veneration and named [[Szentjobb]] (S<U+00E2>niob, Romania) after the relic.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=33}} The relic was kept for centuries in the monastery with the exception during the Mongol invasion of 1241 and 1242, when it was transferred to [[Dubrovnik|Ragusa]] (Dubrovnik, [[Croatia]]).{{sfn|Csorba|2004|p=7}} The Holy Dexter was taken to Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r around 1420.{{sfn|Csorba|2004|p=7}} Following the [[Ottoman Hungary|occupation of the central territories of the Kingdom of Hungary by the Ottoman Turks]] in the middle of the 16th&nbsp;century, the relic was kept in many places, including [[Bosnia]], Ragusa and Vienna.<ref name='Szent_Jobb'>{{cite web |title=A Szent Jobb t<U+00F6>rt<U+00E9>nete [=History of the Holy Dexter]  |work=Szent Istv<U+00E1>n Bazilika: T<U+00F6>rt<U+00E9>net [=St. Stephen's Basilica: History] |publisher=http://www.bazilika.biz |year= 1991 |url=http://www.bazilika.biz/a-szent-jobb-tortenete/a-szent-jobb-tortenete |accessdate=2013-08-19}}</ref> It was returned to Hungary in 1771 when Queen [[Maria Theresa]] (r. 1740<U+2013>1780) donated it to the cloister of the [[Sisters of Loreto]] in Buda.<ref name='Szent_Jobb'/> The relic was kept in the St. Sigismund Chapel in the [[Buda Castle]] between around 1900 and 1944, in a cave near [[Salzburg]] in Austria in 1944 and 1945, by the Sisters of Loreto in Buda between 1945 and 1950, and in the [[St. Stephen's Basilica]] in Budapest since 1950.<ref name='Szent_Jobb'/> An annual procession has celebrated the relic since 1938, but in the period between 1950 and 1987 its celebration was forbidden by the Communist authorities.<ref name='Szent_Jobb'/>

{{Quote|Why is it, brothers, that his other limbs having become disjointed and, his flesh having been reduced to dust, wholly separated, only the right hand, its skin and [[sinews]] adhering to the bones, preserved the beauty of wholeness? I surmise that the inscrutability of divine judgement sought to proclaim by the extraordinary nature of this fact nothing less than that the work of love and alms surpasses the measure of all other virtues. ... The right hand of the blessed man was deservedly exempt from [[putrefaction]], because always reflourishing from the flower of kindness it was never empty from giving gifts to nourish the poor.|''[[Hartvik|Hartvic]], Life of King Stephen of Hungary''<ref>''Hartvic, Life of King Stephen of Hungary'' (ch. 27.), p. 396.</ref>}}

===His ''Admonitions''===
Stephen's ''Greater Legend'' writes that the king "himself compiled a book for his son on moral education".{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|pp=166-167}} This work, now known as ''Admonitions'' or ''De institutione morum'',{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=166}} was preserved in manuscripts written in the [[Late Middle Ages]].{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p=343}} Although scholars debate whether it can actually be attributed to the king or rather to a cleric, most of them agree that it was composed in the first decades of the 11th&nbsp;century.{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p=343}}{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=167}}

The ''Admonitions'' underlines that kingship is inseparably connected with the Catholic faith.{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p=343}}{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=167}} Its author also emphasizes that a monarch is required to make donations to the Church and regularly consult his prelates, but he is entitled to punish clergymen who did wrong.{{sfn|Berend|Laszlovszky|Szak<U+00E1>cs|2007|p=343}} One of the basic ideas expressed in this work was that a sovereign has to cooperate with the "pillars of his rule", meaning the prelates, the aristocrats, the ''isp<U+00E1>ns'' and the warriors.{{sfn|Gy<U+00F6>rffy|1994|p=167}}

{{Quote|My dearest son, if you desire to honor the royal crown, I advise, I counsel, I urge you above all things to maintain the Catholic and Apostolic faith with such diligence and care that you may be an example for all those placed under you by God, and that all the clergy may rightly call you a man of true Christian profession. Failing to do this, you may be sure that you will not be called a Christian or a son of the Church. Indeed, in the royal palace, after the faith itself, the Church holds second place, first constituted and spread through the whole world by His members, the apostles and holy fathers, And though she always produced fresh offspring, nevertheless in certain places she is regarded as ancient. However, dearest son, even now in our kingdom the Church is proclaimed as young and newly planted; and for that reason she needs more prudent and trustworthy guardians less a benefit which the divine mercy bestowed on us undeservedly should be destroyed and annihilated through your idleness, indolence or neglect.|Stephen's ''Admonitions'' to his son, Emeric{{sfn|O'Malley|1995|pp=46-47}}}}

===Artistic representation===
King Stephen of Hungary has been a popular theme in art, especially since the 19th century, with the development of [[Romantic nationalism]]. Paintings, such as ''The Baptism of Vajk'' by [[Gyula Bencz<U+00FA>r]] from 1875), and many statues representing the king throughout Hungary and the neighboring countries testify to Stephen's importance in Hungarian national thought. [[Ferenc Erkel]]'s last complete [[opera]] from 1885, ''Istv<U+00E1>n kir<U+00E1>ly'' ("King Stephen"), was named for him.

Stephen I is also represented in a number of musical compositions.  His best known representation in music was [[Ludwig van Beethoven]]'s ''[[K<U+00F6>nig Stephan|King Stephen Overture]]''.  In 1938, Hungarian composer [[Zolt<U+00E1>n Kod<U+00E1>ly]] wrote a choral piece titled ''Hymn to King Stephen'' ({{lang-hu|<U+00C9>nek Szent Istv<U+00E1>n Kir<U+00E1>lyhoz}}).<ref name=NHQ>{{cite journal|journal=The New Hungarian Quarterly|year=1982|volume=23|page=213|publisher=Corvina Press}}</ref><ref name=Breuer>{{cite book|last=Breuer|first=J<U+00E1>nos|title=Kod<U+00E1>ly-kalauz|year=1982|publisher=Zenem<U+0171>kiad<U+00F3>|isbn=0328473596|pages=293, 318|url=http://books.google.com/books?ei=E_2hUprkC4ORygHkk4DYDA&id=JzEXAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22%C3%89nek+Szent+Istv%C3%A1n+Kir%C3%A1lyhoz%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22%C3%89nek+Szent+Istv%C3%A1n+Kir%C3%A1lyhoz%22+%2B+%221938%22}}</ref>  [[Levente Sz<U+00F6>r<U+00E9>nyi]] and [[J<U+00E1>nos Br<U+00F3>dy]] composed a [[rock opera]], ''[[Istv<U+00E1>n, a kir<U+00E1>ly]]'' ("Stephen, the King"), of the early years of his reign in 1983. A [[sequel]] to it, ''Veled, Uram!'' ("You, Sir!"), was composed in 2000 by Sz<U+00F6>r<U+00E9>nyi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=hu&u=http://vivalamusical.hu/kritikak/veled-uram&prev=/search%3Fq%3DVeled,%2BUram!%26biw%3D800%26bih%3D403|title=Veled, Uram! Izgalmas kir<U+00E1>lydr<U+00E1>ma a Th<U+00E1>li<U+00E1>ban? (You, Sir! King of the exciting drama Thalia Theatre?)|author=Christopher Rechtenwald|date=18 April 2012|publisher=Viva la Musical}}</ref>

